to the nothing to hide argument, there is no threat to privacy unless the government uncovers unlawful activity, in which case a person has no legitimate justification to claim that it remain private.  The nothing to hide argument and its variants are quite prevalent, and thus are worth addressing.  In this essay, Solove critiques the nothing to hide argument and exposes its faulty underpinnings. <P></font><p><font size="2" FACE="Myriad Roman, Arial, Helvetica, Sans-serif;"><b>Keywords:</b> privacy, nothing to hide, data mining, surveillance</font></p></center><font size = "2" FACE="Myriad Roman, Arial, Helvetica, Sans-serif;">Accepted Paper Series</font></div><h4 style="margin-left: 15px;">						Date posted: <font style="font-weight:normal">July 12, 2007</font>; Last revised: <font style="font-weight:normal">May 05, 2008</font></h4><div id="suggestedCitation" class="regtext11"><h4 style="margin-left: 15px; !important; font-weight: bold !important;">Suggested Citation</h4><p style="margin-left: 15px !important; margin-right: 10px !important;" class="regtext11"><div class="simField" style="text-decoration:none;font-size:11px;overflow: hidden;	margin-left: 15px;width: 544px;" >Solove, Daniel J., 'I've Got Nothing to Hide' and Other Misunderstandings of Privacy. San Diego Law Review, Vol. 44, 2007; GWU Law School Public Law Research Paper No. 289. Available at SSRN: http://ssrn.com/abstract=998565</div></p><BLOCKQUOTE><form name="frmExport"><br><FONT size="2" FACE="Myriad Roman, Arial, Helvetica, Sans-serif;">Export to:<select name="cboFormat" style="text-decoration:none;" ><option value="2" >BibTeX</option><option value="1" selected>EndNote</option><option value="3" >RefMan</option><option value="4" >RefWorks</option></select>    <span class="purpleBTN"><a href="#" onClick="location.href='RefExport.cfm?abstract_id=998565&format=' + document.frmExport.cboFormat.value;">Export Citation</a></span><a style="font-size:9px; padding-top: 10px;" cl